
âœ… 1. Python

ğŸ”¸ Implicit:

x = 10     # int
y = 2.5    # float
z = x + y  # z becomes float


ğŸ”¸ Explicit (Type Casting):

int("10")      # string to int
float("3.14")  # string to float
str(42)        # int to string


âœ… 2. PHP

ğŸ”¸ Implicit:

PHP does automatic type juggling.

$x = "10" + 5;   // $x is int(15)


ğŸ”¸ Explicit (Type Casting):

$x = (int)"123";
$y = (float)"3.14";
$z = (string)25;


âœ… 3. MATLAB

ğŸ”¸ Implicit:

MATLAB automatically converts types in expressions.

a = int32(5);
b = 2.5;
c = a + b; % 'a' is promoted to double


ğŸ”¸ Explicit:

x = double(10);     % int to double
y = int8(3.14);     % truncates to int8
z = num2str(25);    % number to string
n = str2double('3.14');  % string to number


âœ… 4. Java

ğŸ”¸ Implicit (Widening):

int x = 10;
double y = x;  // OK


ğŸ”¸ Explicit (Narrowing):

double a = 3.14;
int b = (int) a;   // b = 3 (truncated)


ğŸ”¸ String conversions:

String s = String.valueOf(123);      // int to string
int x = Integer.parseInt("123");     // string to int


âœ… 5. C

ğŸ”¸ Implicit:

int x = 10;
float y = x + 2.5;  // int promoted to float


ğŸ”¸ Explicit:

float f = 3.14;
int i = (int)f;  // truncated


ğŸ”¸ String <-> Number (via library):

#include <stdlib.h>
int x = atoi("123");  // string to int
char str[10];
sprintf(str, "%d", 42);  // int to string


âœ… 6. C++

ğŸ”¸ Implicit:

Same as C.

ğŸ”¸ Explicit (C-style and C++ style):

double d = 3.14;
int i = (int)d;               // C-style cast
int j = static_cast<int>(d);  // C++-style cast


ğŸ”¸ String Conversions (C++11+):

#include <string>
int x = std::stoi("123");      // string to int
std::string s = std::to_string(42);  // int to string


âœ… 7. C#

ğŸ”¸ Implicit:

int x = 123;
double y = x;  // implicit conversion


ğŸ”¸ Explicit:

double d = 3.14;
int i = (int)d;  // explicit cast


ğŸ”¸ String conversions:

int x = int.Parse("123");
string s = 42.ToString();


ğŸ”¸ Using Convert class:

int x = Convert.ToInt32("456");
double y = Convert.ToDouble("3.14");


